##On Day seven of the temporary quarantine, I issued my first death certificate

Wechat, renwumag1980

Feature Introduction, the best Chinese character report

Dr Cai Yi is the head of the Pain Department of Wuhan General Hospital. He specializes in minimally invasive treatment of cervical, lumbar and shoulder pain. Since January 28, he has applied to the front line of the fight against the epidemic and has become a temporary "doctor against the epidemic" .
In less than 10 days, he has managed the fever Ward II of Wuhan's Central Hospital, where he has experienced the deaths of patients, the infections of colleagues and the reshaping of his professional outlook as a doctor.
We noticed him because of one of his friend groups, in which he wrote about the experience of nurses in his department who had contracted COVID-19 pneumonia. It wasn't long. He said he wrote it in less than 20 minutes. But this text of his was captured and went viral on the Internet.
On Feb. 3, Dr. Cai Yi gave an interview to people magazine. The surgeon, who tells the truth and laughs at times during the interview, said he is a "bandit" in his own right and hopes that in the midst of the epidemic, medical staff will be able to convey more than just sadness.
The message he hoped to get out of the interview was: The next two weeks are critical, people must do a good job of home quarantine, don't be sorry for the sacrifice of medical staff; hope someone can donate some breathing machines to Wuhan, to treat more critically ill patients.
Here is his narrative, as if

Dr Cai Yi is the head of the Pain Department of Wuhan General Hospital. He specializes in minimally invasive treatment of cervical, lumbar and shoulder pain. Since January 28, he has applied to the front line of the fight against the epidemic and has become a temporary "doctor against the epidemic" .

In less than 10 days, he has managed the fever Ward II of Wuhan's Central Hospital, where he has experienced the deaths of patients, the infections of colleagues and the reshaping of his professional outlook as a doctor.

We noticed him because of one of his friend groups, in which he wrote about the experience of nurses in his department who had contracted COVID-19 pneumonia. It wasn't long. He said he wrote it in less than 20 minutes. But this text of his was captured and went viral on the Internet.

On Feb. 3, Dr. Cai Yi gave an interview to people magazine. The surgeon, who tells the truth and laughs at times during the interview, said he is a "bandit" in his own right and hopes that in the midst of the epidemic, medical staff will be able to convey more than just sadness.

The message he hoped to get out of the interview was: The next two weeks are critical, people must do a good job of home quarantine, don't be sorry for the sacrifice of medical staff; hope someone can donate some breathing machines to Wuhan, to treat more critically ill patients.

Here is his narrative, as if

By Luo Qian

Editor | Goldstone

1

There is no breathing doctor in our hospital now; the whole hospital is breathing doctor.

I've been on the front line since January 28th. Physicians are not enough, surgeons are trained to be on the front line of support, training is to enhance understanding of this disease, to do some training in the use of drugs, as for the rescue of these, we have seen everything in surgery, we are very familiar with the rescue process. At that time, the hospital almost all surgeons have signed up, I had the honor of the first sign-up, the first up, I do not know what day today, do not remember how long continuous work, just so.

In fact, I did not find so many patients before the first line, into the first line I know how hard we physicians. The First Day at 6 o'clock Ward, 9 o'clock to receive patients, the first day received 19 wards, the next day the ward is full, now our department admitted 33 patients.

My original plan was to bring five male doctors to the front line, and the girls to the second tier, but then I realized I couldn't. Why? First of all, the number of patients exceeded our expectations, and some of them were critically ill, which exceeded my expectations. Third, the protective clothing was very heavy, and the protective glasses often fogged up, so that people could not see clearly or speak clearly from a few meters away, you have to shout at the top of your lungs, which makes you less productive.

When I found out, I shut down the pain clinic in the other wing, putting all the younger doctors on the line. There were 12 doctors in our pain department, only one, a 48-year-old doctor, I let him stay at home, the older one had a bad infection, all the other doctors came, all the nurses from Corey came, so that everyone can work relatively short hours, this is no way.

Two days ago, one of our nurses was infected. I picked up her phone, first heard the sound of crying, my heart on the click. What's the worst thing that can happen to her? Even the hospital knows, and colleagues have to avoid her when they see her again, and if we don't, we're vulnerable to infection. Think about it. Yesterday we were at work together, today we were infected, and the other guys were walking around me. It's hard.

In fact, I also know I should not approach her, but colleagues still have feelings, this is the "head" , there is no way, we saw their colleagues like this, who sent her back? Who consoled her?

I added a mask, asked her home quarantine or hospital, her mood gradually stabilized, said home parents, also do not want to be hospitalized, want to rent a house outside isolation. I said yes, accompany her to get oral medication, to find a place to live. She was quickly evacuated from the home like hotel, where our medical staff were concentrated, and while she was packing up, I told her that I was a little scared, too, so I went to take a hot bath to kill the virus, and then I drove her home, but call the hospital and have them sterilize her place. I was carrying her.

On the way, she still decided to call her mother to inform the situation, her parents crazy to hurry here, she cried insisted not to let her parents come. Finally we went downstairs to get her things, her parents and her boyfriend to see her from a distance, a few words of encouragement, her mother has been crying, I have to interrupt them, "identity card quickly, you go! "! "The nurse was also calm and told her boyfriend to take her parents to the hospital for examination and screening.

Seeing that she was infected, another sick nurse, afraid of being short-handed, cut off her long hair to be on the line. I saw that she wasn't feeling well, and I wanted her to have a couple of days off, but as soon as she saw that one of her co-workers was infected, she said, "I'll take one out, and I'll take the day off. ". I don't know about the rest of the department, but so far, no one in my department has said that I'm sick, that I'm not feeling well, and that I have to leave.

On the contrary, we medical staff and nursing staff, especially nurses, many husbands pull to prevent them from coming, parents pull to prevent them from coming, it is of no use, they cut off the telephone at home, voluntarily sign up, go directly to the line of fire, who encourages them, no one encourages them, they're young girls. And on the front lines, many nurses work longer hours than doctors, which makes me think women are more resilient than men.

Medical staff in the group to take the initiative to register the source of Wuhan Central Hospital Weibo

2

Later, the infected nurse, her parents and boyfriend went to the screening, the results were very bad, the father was also infected, the film than her worse.

Compared with SARS 17 years ago, this time the virus is more transmissible, more covert, and faster, in the incubation period can be infected. Some of the staff at our hospital had no symptoms whatsoever, and they were cleared, and they showed that they were infected. But compared with SARS, its toxicity is relatively weak, older patients, some weak constitution, patients with basic diseases, the risk will be greater, but generally young patients have a good prognosis.

And Its treatment is not quite the same as SARS. The onset of SARS is fairly rapid, and in the early days, you might use large doses of hormones, 500 to 1,000 milligrams of hormones, but this time, we're mostly pushing 40 to 80 milligrams, so 1,000 divided by 40,25 times the dose, it's a big difference. So many people worry about curing the sequelae, such as osteonecrosis of the femoral head and other sequelae of steroid use, in this case, the probability is much lower, so you can relax a little bit.

In the face of an epidemic, the people who know the most about the disease are the health care workers. We all know that we are at risk of infection, but we believe that even if we are young and strong, there will not be too many complications, and even home isolation will have a very good effect, we have the confidence that surgeons are in good shape, and we have a good idea of what it would look like if it got infected.

But when we really know the moment of infection, that mood swings, as a "person" , it is impossible to escape, especially their own family was infected, that kind of guilt is really difficult to describe.

We do a group C.T. once a week. You ever play with that toy? According to the crocodile mouth teeth of the toy, that toy and we take CT the same feeling, press and hold, do not know who is the winning one. You may not have any symptoms, and when you get a CT and you find out you're infected, that's how we feel. The infected nurse in our department had three CT scans, the first two were negative, this one is positive, do you think it can predict? It's impossible to predict.

Each time, the group encouraged each other, and the young doctor in Corey said, "you go first, boss, " and I was usually the first one up. The other two days, I felt very tired and tired, and my eyes were not comfortable. I was afraid that if something happened, I would go to the CT alone at night. I went out to start the car, and my foot was on the accelerator, and my legs were a little weak, because I felt that all my symptoms fit, and I've been up close and personal with these patients, and I'm just so relieved that it turned out okay. So every time CT, we will take CT together, because a person to take really need courage, in case of finding out that he is the one who won the bid, especially need the comfort of colleagues.

In a way, this fear is an instinct. For example, let's say you have a gall bladder that needs to be operated on. You don't panic. You cut the gall bladder, you don't die? We've only been treating the disease for a few weeks now? Who can guarantee that there will be no problems in the future? We are all young people, a lung damage, healed after the impact, you will worry about it, right? And some of the younger ones do, right? And if I'm not lucky, what percentage am I? So it is a shock to happen to yourself. You know the prognosis of this disease is OK, but it is always uncomfortable.

Fortunately, I am still quite "bandit" , I am from Wuhan, we are from Wuhan. My co-workers write their names on the back of their suits every day, and I never write "go, go, go, go. " I always write, "Drug Lord One, " "drug lord two. ". My personality is like this, I am a surgeon, do surgery often encounter various problems, so we have to have a good ability to withstand pressure, to maintain rational optimism.

These days, many students comfort me, encourage me, send me supplies, colleagues also always say, "boss you can not fall, " I said it does not matter, but also joking, the day I was infected and quarantined, I have more time to send friends circle, right?

The infected nurse finally decided to come in, come with her father, live in the same room, I wouldn't encourage her too much, she knew the real situation, she knew the real prognosis, she'll get over the discomfort.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
TUMBLR: Wuhan Central Hospital

3

Before that, I was in the pain department for five years. I mainly did minimally invasive surgery for cervical, lumbar and shoulder pain. I hardly knew how to write a death record. I couldn't write anything down. This morning, a critically ill patient I treated died without resuscitation, i had to learn everything from the ground up. It's true.

The patient, a senior professor in his 60s, had driven himself to the hospital, where it is now a rule that relatives of the deceased with COVID-19 pneumonia are not allowed to see the bodies, which are all handled by funeral homes.

The patient tested positive for nucleic acid, and from his imaging studies, it was almost certainly a diagnosis, but on his death certificate, we could only write about suspected COVID-19 pneumonia, and we couldn't write about a diagnosis until we found out it was positive. For the past two days, everyone has been talking about the diagnostic criteria. Clinically, nucleic acid test is frankly not approved by many doctors, because in many cases, we check it from imaging, for example, through CT, we might be able to get a better look at the lungs. NUCLEIC ACID tests take samples, if you don't take them deep enough, it's likely to be negative, false negative, and it needs to be tested again and again, so what I tell all my patients is not to focus too much on the results of the nucleic acid tests.

The patient passed away, the family had to go back, and the car was very difficult to call. The patient's son went to the United States, to see him off is two old people, one cried badly, is his wife, the other is his brother, two are old people. They have to take the patient's things back, but also to go through various formalities, to sign, take photos, death certificate to upload, two old people how to do? We're the only ones who can help him.

The two old men told me they'd find their own way back, and I said, "what do you want? ". Is this the time to make a phone call and get a designated driver? Let's say we get a designated driver, and we don't tell anyone it's an infected vehicle, okay? Second of all, is there a designated driver in Wuhan? I said, "I'll drive it back for you. Wait for me. ".

I went down with the alcohol to sterilize the car, opened the door a few minutes later, the car radio began to broadcast, scared me. The patient's car was parked in a dark corner on the second floor. The model was unfamiliar to me. The radio went on and I didn't even know how to turn it off. It's real, isn't it? That's the real story around me.

I used to be an anesthesiologist. I've seen many people die and live, but many of the relatives of those who died and lived can accompany me. However, the relatives of the infected patients can not accompany them in life and death. In the end, we are the only ones who can comfort them, there are a lot of patients'families are disgusted with them, some patients brought in, the family members went straight away, or even no family brought in, some patients do not want to infect the family members, their own hospital.

I was in there for three hours in the morning, trying to give him as much oxygen as I could, from 70 to 60 to 50 to 40, by the end of the day, i sent all the young doctors out because there was a high risk of infection. I sent him to the end, there is no more treatment, there is no way to go down, I was inside, sitting with him, that is the feeling.

He didn't give me any last words. He just kept telling me, "don't give up on me. ". When he couldn't keep up with his oxygen, I helped him put his oxygen mask on. Actually, technically, I built this to be very contagious, but I knew that the patient needed someone to calm him down before he left, and maybe there was nothing we could do, but we have to comfort him, we have to give him hope, I encourage him, I say, it's GonNa be okay, it's GonNa be okay, it's GonNa be okay, it's GonNa be all right, it's GonNa be all right until the end.

These emotions are so negative, you see a person to the end of the powerless, only to see him go, and his family can not accompany, you know what kind of feeling?

But don't take it too personally, actually I'm in a good mental state, I can't help it, there are things I can't change, there are diseases I can't cure, then I'll accept it, I still have to treat the patients behind me, I still have over 30 patients, two more came in today, and I have to keep working, and I can't say I'm in a bad mood, so I quit, but what about the patients, what about the patients I'm dealing with?

Some people also say that front-line medical staff need psychological counseling, but now, we have no time for psychological counseling? The psychologist can not enter our hospital, we self-adjustment or mutual adjustment of it, a joke, optimistic point, what else to do? I really can't help it. In the future, when the epidemic has passed, some doctors and nurses on the front line will still have to do some psychological counseling, but this is all for the future.

The hands of medical staff in Wuhan Central Hospital

4

With this outbreak, I'm feeling more and more dependent on the doctor, and I feel like we're kind of needed.

I didn't want to be a doctor. When I took the college entrance exam, my scores got me into Tsinghua University. But my father wanted me to study medicine, so I applied for the Tongji Medical College. After graduation, at first I did anesthesia, the operation was very beautiful, but people did not pay attention to anesthesia, of course, it is normal, later I did pain surgery, in the concept of many Chinese people, pain can be carried over, do not need treatment, but this time, when the lives of many patients are at stake, this need and identification with the doctor outweighs even dependence on family members.

The specificity of this disease determines that we do not communicate with patients so smoothly. After all, we wear protective clothing and protective glasses. Therefore, many of us communicate with patients through groups on Wechat, this is the method that Professor Yang Dong of Concorde Hospital teaches me. We put each group's doctor and his patients in a cluster, and I was in each cluster. That way, even if there's no rounds, if there's anything the patient wants to know, if there's anything we want to tell the patient, we can talk to him as soon as we can.

It's also a way for us to get to know each other better, and for some patients, it's an encouragement. Because some patients will be depressed, others encourage him, his family encourage him, he does not believe, the doctor is a professional after all, if we encourage him, he may be a little bit more trust.

Patients can be very moving. Some of the symptoms of many people, we ask out, we did not go to rounds, even if they breathe, but also forbear not to say, do not ring the Bell, because we are afraid of tired, we are afraid of trouble, we are afraid to infect us.

I had a patient who had to be transferred to Vulcan Mountain Hospital because of the policy, a man in his 50s, he cried directly when he said goodbye to us, he said he was very reluctant to leave, and we all felt very sad. Usually patients give me at most send a banner of what, never this kind of crying, these days, we medical staff and patients like comrades-in-arms, really called heart to heart, usually there is little such a feeling.

These days, a lot of people come to interview me because of my friend circle, I want to say, I have money, I will operate, I have the technology, do not need to do what the net is famous. I sent out a friend circle just to remind the general public that at the beginning, when so many patients came, my heart was flustered. I didn't know when it was a head, and I didn't know if more and more treatments would be given, but later I found that once isolated, the streets of Wuhan were deserted, and I sensed a trend toward a little control, so I just wanted to urge everyone to behave in house quarantine for the next two weeks and live up to the sacrifices of the medical staff.

In terms of materials, we are the biggest third-class hospital in Wuhan, and we are also next to the south China seafood market. We seem to have enough materials at present. What is the difference? The bad stuff is the right stuff, like suits and masks, and we have stuff that's really up to standard, and it's hard. But some brother hospitals smaller than ours are short on basic supplies.

At present, in the face of this disease, we do not have too many methods for the time being. The first treatment for symptomatic diseases, the second to increase immunity, and the third to control complications, there is no more. Patients with severe diseases will either end up with heart failure or failure, now most patients are whoo-hoo-hoo. So the first-line hospitals are most in need of breathing machine. Here, people with money can donate a little good breathing machine, some 20,000 or so non-invasive breathing machine is very good, this kind of breathing machine if a little more, in this period may treat more serious patients.

Finally, I want to say, you must hold on a little longer, hold on. When the epidemic is over, what I'd like to do most is to have a big meal with my colleagues, have a snack and drink beer. People in Wuhan like to have a snack most. This time, I really suffocate.
